rging institutions of the bourgeoisie—coffee houses, periodicals, encyclopedias, literary culture, etc.—was seen as being mediated by the public sphere, making it a symbolic site of public reasoning. This volume examines whether the “public sphere” remains a central explanatory model in the social sciences, political theory, and the humanities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aDemocracyxPhilosophy. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aBorn, Georgina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrowell, Steven G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmden, Christian J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmden, Christian J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGraham, Gordon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHardy, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelty, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMidgley, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMidgley, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTully, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWihl, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilson, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311099828340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780857457226?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780857457226423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780857457226/original  a978-3-11-099828-3  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013c20